1
00:01:29,672 --> 00:01:32,607
I ask you now to pronounce judgment...

2
00:01:32,775 --> 00:01:34,299
...on those accused.

3
00:01:36,779 --> 00:01:38,076
On this...

4
00:01:38,247 --> 00:01:42,411
This mindless aberration,
whose only means of expression...

5
00:01:42,584 --> 00:01:44,950
...are wanton violence and destruction.

6
00:01:46,221 --> 00:01:47,483
On the woman, Ursa...

7
00:01:47,956 --> 00:01:51,187
...whose perversions
and unreasoning hatred of all mankind...

8
00:01:51,694 --> 00:01:55,255
...have threatened even the children
of the planet Krypton.

9
00:01:56,465 --> 00:01:59,195
Finally, General Zod.

10
00:01:59,368 --> 00:02:01,598
Chief architect
of this intended revolution...

11
00:02:01,770 --> 00:02:06,833
...and author of this insidious plot
to establish a new order amongst us...

12
00:02:07,209 --> 00:02:10,736
...with himself as absolute ruler.

13
00:02:11,714 --> 00:02:14,148
The decision of the council
will now be heard.

14
00:02:14,316 --> 00:02:15,613
Guilty.

15
00:02:16,618 --> 00:02:17,812
- Guilty.
- Guilty.

16
00:02:19,788 --> 00:02:21,380
Guilty.

17
00:02:23,726 --> 00:02:25,626
The vote must be unanimous, Jor-EI.

18
00:02:26,628 --> 00:02:29,062
It has therefore
now become your decision.

19
00:02:29,231 --> 00:02:31,563
You alone will condemn us if you wish...

20
00:02:31,734 --> 00:02:34,669
...and you alone
will be held responsible by me.

21
00:02:45,247 --> 00:02:47,715
You will bow down before me, Jor-EI.

22
00:02:47,883 --> 00:02:49,077
I swear it.

23
00:02:49,251 --> 00:02:54,245
No matter that it takes an eternity,
you will bow down before me!

24
00:02:54,423 --> 00:02:55,515
Both you...

25
00:02:55,791 --> 00:02:56,883
...and then one day...

26
00:02:57,059 --> 00:02:58,959
...your heirs!

27
00:03:28,357 --> 00:03:31,918
You will bow down before me!

28
00:03:33,896 --> 00:03:36,262
- Forgive me!
- I'll be back!

29
00:03:36,431 --> 00:03:37,557
Forgive me!

30
00:04:10,632 --> 00:04:15,126
Your mother Lara has sent you
three blankets, of red, yellow and blue.

31
00:04:16,572 --> 00:04:18,972
Their protection
will ensure your strength.

32
00:05:28,577 --> 00:05:32,513
It's kryptonite, Superman.
A little souvenir from the old hometown.

33
00:05:37,686 --> 00:05:42,248
You were great in your day, Superman.
But it just stands to reason...

34
00:05:42,424 --> 00:05:44,858
...when it came time
to cash in your chips...

35
00:05:45,027 --> 00:05:48,463
...this old, diseased maniac...

36
00:05:48,630 --> 00:05:50,564
...would be your banker.

37
00:05:54,002 --> 00:05:55,936
Mind over muscle.

38
00:06:29,705 --> 00:06:31,900
Why did you kiss me first?

39
00:06:33,175 --> 00:06:36,201
Lt... I didn't think you'd let me later.

40
00:06:36,378 --> 00:06:38,175
Stand aside, now.

41
00:08:15,343 --> 00:08:17,368
Free!

42
00:12:01,970 --> 00:12:05,906
Nice fresh melons.
Nice fresh melons. Get them fresh here.

43
00:12:06,074 --> 00:12:08,941
Good for the cooking, huh?
Look at this, the best.

44
00:12:10,712 --> 00:12:13,237
"Lex Luthor's scheme bombs.
Superman saves nation.

45
00:12:13,415 --> 00:12:16,851
Master criminal draws harsh sentence.
Exclusive story by Lois Lane.

46
00:12:17,018 --> 00:12:19,145
Photographs by James Olsen."

47
00:12:19,321 --> 00:12:22,518
Luthor, you never looked lovelier.

48
00:12:22,691 --> 00:12:23,851
Lois, terrific job.

49
00:12:24,025 --> 00:12:25,993
- Thanks, chief.
- Great story, really great.

50
00:12:26,161 --> 00:12:28,356
Hey, good morning, chief. You're late.

51
00:12:28,530 --> 00:12:31,431
Yeah, Miss Lane, that's a great story.
One of the best.

52
00:12:31,599 --> 00:12:35,933
Well, Jimmy, usually a picture isn't worth
a thousand words when I write the story...

53
00:12:36,104 --> 00:12:37,935
...but in this case, congratulations.

54
00:12:38,106 --> 00:12:39,471
- Yeah, thanks a lot.
- Yeah.

55
00:12:40,542 --> 00:12:43,978
There's Mr. Kent. Bet he wishes
he'd been around when it all happened.

56
00:12:44,145 --> 00:12:46,670
Clark, he's never around
when Superman appears.

57
00:12:46,848 --> 00:12:48,338
Poor guy.

58
00:12:57,525 --> 00:12:59,152
- You got a page in the front?
- Yeah.

59
00:13:02,263 --> 00:13:04,595
Miss Lane got the best story.

60
00:13:11,973 --> 00:13:13,907
Good morning, Lois.

61
00:13:15,276 --> 00:13:16,573
Hi.

62
00:13:54,048 --> 00:13:56,346
Lane, Kent, get in here!

63
00:13:56,518 --> 00:13:58,349
Now, see, Jimmy,
you got me in trouble.

64
00:13:58,520 --> 00:14:01,683
- We were talking.
- So long. A big mistake.

65
00:14:02,524 --> 00:14:04,856
Next time, don't do that to me.

66
00:14:05,193 --> 00:14:08,822
- Good morning, Lois. How are you today?
- Oh, I'm just super. Thanks.

67
00:14:08,997 --> 00:14:10,658
- Good morning, Mr. White.
- I'm super.

68
00:14:10,832 --> 00:14:14,199
- Yeah, morning. You're late, Kent.
- I know. I'm sorry, Mr. White.

69
00:14:14,369 --> 00:14:16,633
- I got stuck in traffic.
- Oh, that's a new one.

70
00:14:16,805 --> 00:14:18,568
- Excuse me?
- I mean, as opposed to:

71
00:14:18,740 --> 00:14:22,198
"I was stuck in a phone booth" or
"I got locked into the men's bathroom."

72
00:14:22,377 --> 00:14:25,005
Lois, what are you talking about?
I'm sorry I was late.

73
00:14:25,180 --> 00:14:27,944
If you two wanna bicker,
I have just the assignment for you.

74
00:14:28,116 --> 00:14:32,109
You're gonna pose as a honeymoon couple
to get an expose on the newlywed racket.

75
00:14:32,287 --> 00:14:35,984
Some of those hotels are bilking
those poor kids for every cent they can get.

76
00:14:36,157 --> 00:14:39,388
Real human-interest stuff.
Make your Aunt Hattie cry her eyes out.

77
00:14:39,661 --> 00:14:42,687
- Newlyweds?
- That is a great idea, Mr. White.

78
00:14:42,864 --> 00:14:46,493
- I'm sorry, but I'm in the middle of a series...
- I mean, it wouldn't take long.

79
00:14:46,668 --> 00:14:51,162
We could just fly right up there
and zoom back down again.

80
00:14:51,339 --> 00:14:53,603
No, Superman?

81
00:14:53,775 --> 00:14:56,972
Yeah. If he'd give you two a ride,
maybe we could save a couple bucks.

82
00:14:57,245 --> 00:14:59,611
I gotta see young Olsen.
Six lousy photographs...

83
00:14:59,781 --> 00:15:04,218
...and that kid's hitting me up for a raise.
- Excuse me. Mr. White? Could we talk?

84
00:15:04,385 --> 00:15:05,909
Darn.

85
00:15:06,855 --> 00:15:09,756
You look like the cat who swallowed
the canary this morning.

86
00:15:09,924 --> 00:15:13,758
A canary? No, actually I was
thinking of something bigger...

87
00:15:13,928 --> 00:15:16,897
...something that flies,
something more in blue.

88
00:15:17,365 --> 00:15:19,333
Lois, as usual, I'm totally in the dark...

89
00:15:19,501 --> 00:15:22,732
Let me just turn on the lights
for you then.

90
00:15:24,639 --> 00:15:26,402
Get the picture?

91
00:15:28,309 --> 00:15:31,904
I didn't put this together until
this morning. Which is really strange...

92
00:15:32,080 --> 00:15:35,379
...because a good reporter isn't supposed to
let anything slip by her.

93
00:15:35,550 --> 00:15:37,984
Well, that's very amusing. Yes.

94
00:15:38,152 --> 00:15:39,619
- Excuse me.
- Amusing?

95
00:15:39,787 --> 00:15:44,190
- Yes, sirree, that's... That's very amusing.
- Amusing, huh?

96
00:15:44,425 --> 00:15:48,521
Tall, broad shoulders...

97
00:15:48,930 --> 00:15:50,955
...dark hair.

98
00:15:51,132 --> 00:15:54,067
Gotta give you credit,
you really had me fooled.

99
00:15:54,235 --> 00:15:56,829
And I'm nobody's fool...

100
00:15:57,639 --> 00:15:59,368
...Superman.

101
00:15:59,841 --> 00:16:01,172
Superman?

102
00:16:01,342 --> 00:16:05,506
You mean you think I'm Superman?

103
00:16:06,147 --> 00:16:09,275
- Willing to bet my life on it.
- Lois, you know, you are priceless.

104
00:16:09,450 --> 00:16:12,442
Really. That is the single most
ridiculous thing I've ever...

105
00:16:13,855 --> 00:16:16,722
- Lois, what are you doing?
- You wouldn't let me die, Superman.

106
00:16:56,698 --> 00:17:00,361
- Oh, God.
- Help her out. Help her out.

107
00:17:00,768 --> 00:17:03,566
- Clark!
- Lois, what have you done?

108
00:17:03,972 --> 00:17:06,600
Clark, the... You're not...

109
00:17:09,210 --> 00:17:12,543
Hey, Clark, you seen Lois?

110
00:17:15,483 --> 00:17:17,280
She just stepped out for a minute.

111
00:17:34,702 --> 00:17:37,694
This is how it ends for
the greatest criminal mind of our time.

112
00:17:37,872 --> 00:17:40,136
Not with a whimper, not with a bang.

113
00:17:40,308 --> 00:17:42,833
How do they choose
to reward Lex Luthor...

114
00:17:43,011 --> 00:17:44,945
...the greatest genius in this world?

115
00:17:45,113 --> 00:17:49,015
Do they give him glory or treasure?
What, matter of fact, do they give him?

116
00:17:49,183 --> 00:17:53,279
Life plus 25, Luthor. Get to work.

117
00:17:57,592 --> 00:18:00,220
Don't feel bad, Mr. Luthor.
It almost worked.

118
00:18:00,395 --> 00:18:03,228
I mean, California almost
fell down, right in the ocean.

119
00:18:03,398 --> 00:18:05,195
Millions of people was almost killed.

120
00:18:05,366 --> 00:18:08,563
If it hadn't been for that guy
Superman, that overgrown Boy Scout.

121
00:18:08,736 --> 00:18:11,967
- I want my Liberace record back tonight.
- Tonight?

122
00:18:12,140 --> 00:18:17,203
What are you gonna do with a guy like that?
He flies around so fast and everything.

123
00:18:18,212 --> 00:18:21,409
I mean, they can't even trace
that guy on that radar they got.

124
00:18:21,616 --> 00:18:24,551
Every time they try, he just flies off.

125
00:18:24,719 --> 00:18:26,084
- Where?
- North.

126
00:18:26,287 --> 00:18:28,084
Why?

127
00:18:28,256 --> 00:18:29,553
To ski?

128
00:18:29,724 --> 00:18:33,125
Otis, every man has his vulnerable point.

129
00:18:33,294 --> 00:18:36,525
Some, like you, Otis,
have more than one.

130
00:18:36,698 --> 00:18:38,632
I didn't see Superman's in time.

131
00:18:38,800 --> 00:18:42,429
But now, through patience,
invention, and skill...

132
00:18:43,471 --> 00:18:46,565
...my little black box
is just about ready.

133
00:18:46,741 --> 00:18:49,972
Oh, that little black box in our cell?

134
00:18:52,980 --> 00:18:56,040
That little black box, Mr. Luthor...

135
00:18:57,585 --> 00:18:59,485
...what's it for?

136
00:18:59,654 --> 00:19:05,456
That little black box goes beyond
any normal, conventional radar.

137
00:19:05,626 --> 00:19:08,288
It tracks alpha waves.

138
00:19:10,798 --> 00:19:13,460
Alpha waves. Yeah.

139
00:19:13,634 --> 00:19:16,364
I could've said it tracked pasta e fagioli,
couldn't I?

140
00:19:16,537 --> 00:19:20,166
Oh, with garlic, Mr. Luthor. And butter.

141
00:19:20,341 --> 00:19:21,740
Boy.

142
00:19:24,912 --> 00:19:30,475
Those alpha waves will
take me north to his secret.

143
00:19:30,651 --> 00:19:35,384
And when I have his secret,
I'll have Superman.

144
00:19:38,259 --> 00:19:41,023
Slasher Fogelstein's a bed wetter.

145
00:19:45,666 --> 00:19:49,602
Slasher Fogelstein's a bed wetter.
Pass it.

146
00:19:55,076 --> 00:19:57,010
Hi, Mr. Fogelstein.

147
00:19:57,478 --> 00:20:00,003
- Too fast. Can you get the speed right?

148
00:20:00,181 --> 00:20:03,116
I told you, they installed those
three weeks ago.

149
00:20:04,051 --> 00:20:05,040
Hey.

150
00:20:05,953 --> 00:20:10,151
You follow the bouncing ball for a while.
Thing's giving me a headache.

151
00:20:10,324 --> 00:20:13,418
Anyway, somebody's
gotta check up on those guys.

152
00:20:13,594 --> 00:20:16,427
Yeah, I keep on forgetting about them.

153
00:20:16,597 --> 00:20:19,361
How long they been up there, 45 days?

154
00:20:19,534 --> 00:20:22,469
The whole world's forgotten about it.

155
00:20:24,705 --> 00:20:26,866
Houston calling Artemis II.

156
00:20:27,675 --> 00:20:30,508
Houston calling Artemis II. Come in.

157
00:20:30,678 --> 00:20:33,238
Morning, Houston. Hold on, Nate.

158
00:20:33,414 --> 00:20:35,348
- Yo.
- How are things going?

159
00:20:36,117 --> 00:20:38,585
All systems normal, Houston.

160
00:20:38,753 --> 00:20:41,654
Andy is out doing the geological survey.

161
00:20:41,823 --> 00:20:44,121
More rocks. Nice.

162
00:20:44,292 --> 00:20:47,386
And cosmonaut Boris
is getting some soil samples.

163
00:20:47,562 --> 00:20:50,122
By the way, Boris and I are engaged.

164
00:20:50,631 --> 00:20:53,759
I had a feeling about you guys
when I saw your Rorschach tests.

165
00:20:53,935 --> 00:20:56,233
Just a little detente
humor there, Houston.

166
00:20:56,404 --> 00:20:58,395
Surface conditions unchanged?

167
00:20:58,573 --> 00:21:01,599
Well, it's mighty
pretty out there. Mighty...

168
00:21:03,744 --> 00:21:05,803
...pretty.
- Mighty pretty.

169
00:21:06,013 --> 00:21:08,140
Right.

170
00:21:08,516 --> 00:21:10,381
Look, Nate?

171
00:21:10,551 --> 00:21:12,143
Nate, wake up, will you?

172
00:21:12,320 --> 00:21:14,880
That's it. I'm dreaming.

173
00:21:15,056 --> 00:21:17,320
Artemis, come in.

174
00:21:17,525 --> 00:21:21,586
Well, Houston, we seem to have
an unidentified flying object.

175
00:21:21,762 --> 00:21:23,161
Unidentified?

176
00:21:23,831 --> 00:21:26,459
- What does it look like?
- Well...

177
00:21:26,634 --> 00:21:29,330
...a lot like a girl.

178
00:21:50,658 --> 00:21:52,455
You.

179
00:21:53,194 --> 00:21:56,686
- What kind of a creature are you?
- Just a man.

180
00:21:57,465 --> 00:21:59,558
A man?

181
00:22:56,324 --> 00:22:59,054
What a fragile sort of life form this is.

182
00:23:24,418 --> 00:23:27,080
Houston, come in. Come in, Houston.

183
00:23:35,596 --> 00:23:36,995
Come in, Houston. Come in.

184
00:23:37,164 --> 00:23:38,791
Attempting manual liftoff.

185
00:23:39,000 --> 00:23:40,228
Can somebody hear me?

186
00:23:40,701 --> 00:23:42,532
Houston!

187
00:23:43,537 --> 00:23:44,663
Come on.

188
00:23:47,541 --> 00:23:49,338
Come on, Houston!

189
00:23:50,211 --> 00:23:52,645
Oh, no. No!

190
00:23:53,180 --> 00:23:55,045
Somebody help me!

191
00:24:01,622 --> 00:24:04,614
- Artemis, Houston calling. Come in.
- What's going on?

192
00:24:04,792 --> 00:24:08,228
- I don't know. We've lost contact.
- So?

193
00:24:08,396 --> 00:24:10,091
Well, we really...

194
00:24:10,698 --> 00:24:12,529
Artemis, come in, please.

195
00:24:14,869 --> 00:24:18,566
All right, which one of you guys
is using the hair dryer?

196
00:24:20,908 --> 00:24:25,743
Strange. I tore those
metal fibers like paper.

197
00:24:25,913 --> 00:24:29,849
And what he did was amazing.

198
00:24:30,017 --> 00:24:34,454
- Something is happening.
- Yes, to all of us.

199
00:24:36,657 --> 00:24:40,855
The closer we come to an
atmosphere with only one sun...

200
00:24:41,028 --> 00:24:42,859
...a yellow sun...

201
00:24:43,030 --> 00:24:46,989
...the more our molecular
density gives us unlimited powers.

202
00:24:47,168 --> 00:24:48,965
They come from there.

203
00:24:49,136 --> 00:24:51,127
A place called Houston.

204
00:24:51,305 --> 00:24:53,705
Then we will go there too...

205
00:24:53,874 --> 00:24:55,808
...to rule.

206
00:24:56,277 --> 00:24:58,939
Finally, to rule.

207
00:25:09,423 --> 00:25:11,152
Three-eighty-two, out.

208
00:25:12,059 --> 00:25:14,425
Three-eighty-three, out.

209
00:25:15,196 --> 00:25:17,460
Three-eighty-four, out.

210
00:25:18,432 --> 00:25:20,730
Three-eighty-five, out.

211
00:25:24,105 --> 00:25:26,437
Lights out, Luthor.

212
00:25:27,007 --> 00:25:29,237
I said, lights out.

213
00:25:31,812 --> 00:25:35,509
You guys are about 10 seconds
away from solitary, you know that?

214
00:25:37,618 --> 00:25:39,643
I told you to...

215
00:25:55,136 --> 00:25:57,297
Freeze, freeze.

216
00:26:30,171 --> 00:26:32,071
Mr. Luthor.

217
00:26:33,407 --> 00:26:35,898
- How we gonna get over that wall?
- How'd we get in?

218
00:26:36,710 --> 00:26:39,270
- We flew in here, remember?
- That's how we'll get out.

219
00:26:39,446 --> 00:26:41,778
Oh, no, not that guy.

220
00:26:45,586 --> 00:26:47,315
Did you just go "psst"?

221
00:26:47,488 --> 00:26:50,651
I wish I had, Mr. Luthor, before we left.

222
00:26:52,293 --> 00:26:54,557
Not that "psst," that "psst."

223
00:26:57,932 --> 00:27:00,730
- Don't go "psst" when I go "psst."
- You do it.

224
00:27:04,238 --> 00:27:06,399
Go out there and find it.

225
00:27:07,107 --> 00:27:11,567
- What am I looking for?
- You'll know when you see it.

226
00:27:22,756 --> 00:27:25,452
I think I found it.

227
00:27:30,631 --> 00:27:32,496
What is it?

228
00:27:33,500 --> 00:27:36,367
It's a ladder, you dummy.

229
00:27:37,137 --> 00:27:38,570
Hi, Miss Teschmacher.

230
00:27:47,548 --> 00:27:48,708
Come on.

231
00:27:49,516 --> 00:27:53,145
Hurry up. Hurry up.

232
00:27:53,721 --> 00:27:55,951
Come on, hurry.

233
00:27:56,957 --> 00:27:59,323
Otis, hold that ladder. Hurry up.

234
00:27:59,493 --> 00:28:03,327
- Yard line, touchdown!
Oh, what a beautiful play.

235
00:28:03,497 --> 00:28:06,227
But there's a marker downfield.
It could be against...

236
00:28:11,805 --> 00:28:12,863
- Come up.
- Come on.

237
00:28:13,040 --> 00:28:15,634
Here I come, Mr. Luthor.

238
00:28:17,411 --> 00:28:18,571
- Get off. Get off.
- Otis!

239
00:28:20,381 --> 00:28:23,077
- We're sinking!
- Get off, get off!

240
00:28:40,100 --> 00:28:42,261
Very good,
Miss Teschmacher. Very good.

241
00:28:42,436 --> 00:28:45,132
- What am I doing here? Why am I here?
- Miss Teschmacher...

242
00:28:45,306 --> 00:28:47,206
...is this a philosophy seminar?

243
00:28:47,374 --> 00:28:49,103
- No. This is a getaway.
- No.

244
00:28:49,276 --> 00:28:50,504
- Getaway.
- Right.

245
00:28:50,678 --> 00:28:53,670
It's ingenious. I don't know
where you got the inspiration from.

246
00:28:53,847 --> 00:28:55,576
